In Mongoose, when you want to link one document to multiple documents (like a customer having multiple orders), you can handle it in three ways:

🪧Embedding (Storing Directly):
In this approach, you store related data directly inside the main document. For example, if you have a user with multiple addresses, you can store all addresses inside the user’s document. This is simple and fast because you don’t need to look up data from other places. However, if the list of addresses becomes large or needs frequent updates, it can slow things down. This works well when the data is small and doesn’t change often — like storing a user’s basic profile details.

🪧Referencing (Storing IDs):
Here, instead of storing all the data directly, you store the IDs of related documents. For example, a customer’s order list might just store the order IDs, and you can use populate() to load the actual order details when needed. This keeps the documents small and makes it easier to handle large datasets or updates. However, reading data is a bit slower since MongoDB has to look up data from different places. This is best when the dataset is large or you need to modify data often — like handling multiple customer orders in an e-commerce app.

🪧Hybrid (Mix of Both):
In this approach, you store basic details (like the order name) directly in the main document and keep an ID reference to the full data. For example, a customer’s order list might store the order name and also an ID to the full order details. This gives you the benefit of fast access for basic data and flexibility to load full details when needed. This works best when you need quick access to common details but still want the ability to handle large datasets — like showing a product name in a shopping cart but loading full details only when the user clicks on it.

✅ Best Approach Based on Situation:
Embedding → Small, simple, and rarely changing data.
Referencing → Large, complex, and frequently updated data.
Hybrid → Fast access to common details + scalable for large datasets.